Leadership Principle: Customer Obsession
Description: Leaders start with the customer and work backwards. They work vigorously to earn and keep customer trust. Although leaders pay attention to competitors, they obsess over customers.

Expected Behaviour:

Takes actions guided by customer input
Works backwards from the optimal customer experience
Tries to surprise and delight the customer
Applies time and energy to make the customer experience more efficient or enjoyable
Identifies new ways of gathering feedback from customers
Listens to feedback from customers and uses it to make improvements
Pushes back when necessary to ensure that decisions consider what is best for customer in the long-term
Earns customers trust by delivering promised services and products which meet or exceed expectations
Stops activities that no longer enhance the customer experience
Concerning Behaviour:

Makes decisions or takes actions without adequately considering the customer impact
Fails to collect or respond to customer input appropriately
Fails to meet customer commitments
Loses and doesn't regain customers' trust
Develops a project approach based on industry trends rather than customer needs
Unable to identify primary customers
Leadership Principle: Bias for Action
Description: Speed matters in business. Many decisions and actions are reversible and do not need extensive study. We value calculated risk taking.

Expected Behaviour:

Takes calculated risks where speed is critical
Gathers information and responds immediately
Makes decisions with limited information when necessary
Moves quickly to address issues and removes barriers to progress
Balances speed with the need for diverse perspectives
Concerning Behaviour:

Hesitates to act due to lack of complete information
Fails to make timely decisions
Ignores input from others when making quick decisions
Fails to address obstacles promptly
Leadership Principle: Are Right, A Lot
Description: Leaders are right a lot. They have strong judgment and good instincts. They seek diverse perspectives and work to disconfirm their beliefs.

Expected Behaviour:

Uses data and evidence to make decisions
Seeks diverse perspectives to validate assumptions
Adapts to new information and adjusts decisions accordingly
Demonstrates strong judgment in ambiguous situations
Concerning Behaviour:

Makes decisions without sufficient data or evidence
Ignores contrary evidence or feedback
Sticks to incorrect decisions despite new information
Fails to seek diverse perspectives
Leadership Principle: Dive Deep
Description: Leaders operate at all levels, stay connected to the details, audit frequently, and are skeptical when metrics and anecdotes differ. No task is beneath them.

Expected Behaviour:

Investigates deeply into problems to find root causes
Uses detailed data to drive decisions
Remains connected to the details of operations
Audits regularly to ensure accuracy
Concerning Behaviour:

Makes decisions based on surface-level information
Fails to investigate anomalies or discrepancies
Relies on high-level summaries without digging into details
Avoids auditing or checking the accuracy of information
Leadership Principle: Earn Trust
Description: Leaders listen attentively, speak candidly, and treat others respectfully. They are vocally self-critical, even when doing so is awkward or embarrassing. Leaders do not believe their or their team’s body odor smells of perfume. They benchmark themselves and their teams against the best.

Expected Behaviour:

Communicates transparently and honestly
Listens actively and respects others' opinions
Admits mistakes and takes responsibility
Builds trust through consistent actions and integrity
Concerning Behaviour:

Fails to listen or dismisses others' opinions
Hides mistakes or avoids taking responsibility
Erodes trust through inconsistent actions
Communicates dishonestly or opaquely
Leadership Principle: Frugality
Description: Accomplish more with less. Constraints breed resourcefulness, self-sufficiency, and invention. There are no extra points for growing headcount, budget size, or fixed expense.

Expected Behaviour:

Finds cost-effective solutions to problems
Maximizes resources and minimizes waste
Demonstrates resourcefulness in achieving goals
Balances cost and quality effectively
Concerning Behaviour:

Wastes resources or fails to control costs
Seeks additional resources without justifying need
Fails to find creative solutions to constraints
Sacrifices quality unnecessarily to save costs
Leadership Principle: Have Backbone; Disagree and Commit
Description: Leaders are obligated to respectfully challenge decisions when they disagree, even when doing so is uncomfortable or exhausting. Leaders have conviction and are tenacious. They do not compromise for the sake of social cohesion. Once a decision is determined, they commit wholly.

Expected Behaviour:

Challenges decisions respectfully when in disagreement
Demonstrates conviction and tenacity in advocating for their viewpoint
Commits fully to decisions once made
Balances dissent with respect for the decision-making process
Concerning Behaviour:

Avoids challenging decisions to maintain harmony
Lacks conviction or gives up easily
Undermines decisions after they are made
Disrespects others' viewpoints during disagreements
Leadership Principle: Hire and Develop the Best
Description: Leaders raise the performance bar with every hire and promotion. They recognize exceptional talent, and willingly move them throughout the organization. Leaders develop leaders and take seriously their role in coaching others.

Expected Behaviour:

Sets high standards for hiring and promotion
Identifies and develops exceptional talent
Invests in the growth and development of team members
Coaches and mentors others effectively
Concerning Behaviour:

Lowers standards to fill positions quickly
Fails to recognize or develop talent
Neglects the development of team members
Provides ineffective or no coaching and feedback
Leadership Principle: Insist on the Highest Standards
Description: Leaders have relentlessly high standards — many people may think these standards are unreasonably high. Leaders continually raise the bar and drive their teams to deliver high-quality products, services, and processes. Leaders ensure that defects do not get sent down the line and that problems are fixed so they stay fixed.

Expected Behaviour:

Maintains high standards for quality and performance
Continuously raises the bar for team performance
Ensures problems are fixed permanently
Drives teams to deliver exceptional results
Concerning Behaviour:

Accepts subpar performance or quality
Fails to address recurring problems
Neglects to raise performance standards
Allows defects to persist
Leadership Principle: Invent and Simplify
Description: Leaders expect and require innovation and invention from their teams and always find ways to simplify. They are externally aware, look for new ideas from everywhere, and are not limited by “not invented here.” As we do new things, we accept that we may be misunderstood for long periods of time.

Expected Behaviour:

Drives innovation and invention
Simplifies complex processes or problems
Seeks new ideas from diverse sources
Accepts the possibility of being misunderstood
Concerning Behaviour:

Avoids innovation or invention
Overcomplicates processes or solutions
Ignores external ideas or perspectives
Fears being misunderstood or taking risks
Leadership Principle: Learn and Be Curious
Description: Leaders are never done learning and always seek to improve themselves. They are curious about new possibilities and act to explore them.

Expected Behaviour:

Continuously seeks to learn and improve
Explores new possibilities and opportunities
Demonstrates curiosity and a willingness to explore
Adapts and grows based on new knowledge
Concerning Behaviour:

Resists learning or new ideas
Avoids exploring new possibilities
Lacks curiosity or willingness to adapt
Fails to seek personal or professional growth
Leadership Principle: Ownership
Description: Leaders act on behalf of the entire company, beyond just their own team. They think long term and don’t sacrifice long-term value for short-term results. They act on behalf of the entire company, never say “that’s not my job.”

Expected Behaviour:

Takes responsibility for company-wide success
Thinks and plans for the long term
Demonstrates ownership beyond their immediate role
Balances short-term and long-term goals effectively
Concerning Behaviour:

Neglects company-wide responsibilities
Focuses only on short-term results
Avoids taking ownership beyond their role
Sacrifices long-term value for immediate gains
Leadership Principle: Think Big
Description: Thinking small is a self-fulfilling prophecy. Leaders create and communicate a bold direction that inspires results. They think differently and look around corners for ways to serve customers.

Expected Behaviour:

Sets and communicates bold, inspiring goals
Thinks creatively and innovatively
Anticipates future needs and opportunities
Inspires others to think big and achieve ambitious goals
Concerning Behaviour:

Sets uninspiring or limited goals
Fails to think creatively or innovatively
Neglects to anticipate future needs
Limits the team's potential with small thinking
Leadership Principle: Strive to Be Earth’s Best Employer
Description: Leaders work every day to create a safer, more productive, higher performing, more diverse, and more just work environment. They lead with empathy, have fun at work, and make it easy for others to have fun. Leaders ask themselves: Are my fellow employees growing? Are they empowered? Are they ready for what’s next? Leaders have a vision for and commitment to their employees’ personal success, whether that be at Amazon or elsewhere.

Expected Behaviour:

Creates a safe and inclusive work environment
Empowers employees and supports their growth
Leads with empathy and fosters a fun workplace
Commits to the
personal success of employees

Concerning Behaviour:

Creates an unsafe or exclusive work environment
Neglects employee growth and empowerment
Lacks empathy or fails to foster a fun workplace
Disregards the personal success of employees
Leadership Principle: Success and Scale Bring Broad Responsibility
Description: We started in a garage, but we’re not there anymore. We are big, we impact the world, and we are far from perfect. We must be humble and thoughtful about even the secondary effects of our actions. Our local communities, planet, and future generations need us to be better every day. We must begin each day with a determination to make better, do better, and be better for our customers, our employees, our partners, and the world at large. And we must end every day knowing we can do even more tomorrow. Leaders create more than they consume and always leave things better than how they found them.

Expected Behaviour:

Evaluates the broad implications of their actions at scale
Makes decisions by weighing the benefits and potential downstream consequences
Recognizes what is effective today may not be appropriate for tomorrow
Actively listens and asks the right questions to find ways to make a difference
Concerning Behaviour:

Possesses a narrow view of reach in the world
Doesn’t evaluate the impact of their actions at scale
Makes decisions to optimize for success regardless of the costs
Dismisses identified areas for improvement
